content:
"12 Monkeys" is inspired by "La Jet√©e" (1962, Chris Marker), a short movie of 28 minutes consisting mainly of a collection of stills.Its main themes are:outbreak of a deadly virus;
time travelling;
psychiatry, what is normal and what is crazy?1995 was a good year for films about viruses. Apart from "12 Monkeys" also "Outbreak" (Wolfgang Petersen) was released. In "12 Monkeys" the outbreak of the virus and the dystopian future it produces is however not the main theme of the film but more the motivation behind the time travelling.Time travelling leads to all sorts of paradoxes. One of the most beautiful of which is in my opinion still the one in "Back to the future" (1985, Robert Zemeckis). A boy travels into the past, meets his mother as a teenager, his mother falls in love with him and the boy must do his utmost to match-make between his father and his mother because otherwise he wouldn't be born. In "back to the future the main character travels back to a time before he was born, in "12 Monkeys" the main character travels back to a time after he was born. This gives rise to another paradox: meeting yourself.Still I don't believe playing with time travel paradoxes is the essence of the film. I would like to call attention to another aspect. When the main character arrives in his past he is making strange statements in the ears of the other characters, his past is their present. They think his is crazy and put him in a madhouse. With the passage of time there occurs a remarkable change of roles. The main character, staying amidst of psychiatric patients all the time begins to think that maybe he is crazy after all and only imagines himself the time travel stuff. The treating psychiatrist on the other hand, noting that some of the strange statements of the main character are coming true, begins to doubt more and more about his mental state.For me this is the essence of the film. What is sane, what is insane and who is to judge?

Story-line => 3/5 (The plot was nice and complex but there were some major loose ends regarding time theories and etc.);
Acting => 4/5 (Some part of acting seemed forced. The rest is top-notch.);
Directing => 5/5 (Directing was topnotch. Had to keep the focus the whole time.);
Visual Effects/Animation => 4/5 (Could have been better.);
Screenplay => 5/5 (This part is generally messed up in case of complicated plots. They handled this very nicely.);
Personal Recommendation => 4/5 (Liked the way it was portrayed. But really disliked forced acting in some places and the loose ends.);
Most Favorite Character => Jeffrey(Acted like a crazy nut as he was supposed to. Loved his acting and role.);Overall Personal Rating => 8.3/10
